{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"849912b6-c6e0-43a4-8667-5230abb2696a","content":"\n\nIn your `App.xaml.cs`, override `CreateWindow` and subscribe to the lifecycle events on the returned `Window`:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);\n\n    window.Created      += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Created\");\n    window.Activated    += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Activated\");\n    window.Deactivated  += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Deactivated\");\n    window.Stopped      += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Stopped\");\n    window.Resumed      += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Resumed\");\n    window.Destroying   += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Destroying\");\n    window.Backgrounding += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Backgrounding\");\n\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\n**Lifecycle order (typical):**\n\n| Transition | Events |\n|---|---|\n| App launch | `Created → Activated` |\n| Sent to background | `Deactivated → Stopped` |\n| Returned to foreground | `Resumed → Activated` |\n| App closed | `Deactivated → Stopped → Destroying` |\n\n> `Backgrounding` is **iOS/Mac Catalyst only** — it fires when the app enters the background, giving you a chance to save state.\n\nReplace `Debug.WriteLine` with your preferred logger (e.g., `ILogger`, Serilog) for production diagnostics.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"eaa9b481-ca33-4f85-a607-24d786cfa9d0","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI Window lifecycle events and how to subscribe to them for logging/debugging. This is a general knowledge question — I can answer it directly without needing to explore any codebase.","outputTokens":442},"id":"374b6c1b-935e-4a4b-b863-45b5154e154a","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:40:00.187Z","parentId":"602d9b8c-638e-427f-af22-249b46496fb9"}
